es in Chaucer's masterpiece of love found and love lost are explored here. Collectively the essays address the question of what it means to be a man in theMiddle Ages, what constitutes masculinity in this era, and how such masculinities are culturally constructed; they seek to advance scholarly understanding of the themes, characters, and actions of Troilus and Criseyde through thehermeneutics of medieval and modern concepts of manliness. Throughout, they argue that Troilus and the other characters, including Criseyde, are subject to multiple and conflicting interpretations, especially in regard to the intersections of their genders with their sexual performances and their conflicted relationships to generic expectations for gendered conduct. Contributors: JOHN M. BOWERS, MICHAEL CALABRESE, HOLLY A. CROCKER, KATE KOPPELMAN,MOLLY MARTIN, MARCIA SMITH MARZEC, GRETCHEN MIESZKOWSKI, JAMES J. PAXSON, TISON PUGH, R. ALLEN SHOAF, ROBERT S. STURGES, ANGELA JANE WEISL, RICHARD ZEIKOWITZ  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCressida (Fictitious character). 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMasculinityxHistory. 0aMen in literature. 0aTroilus (Legendary character) in literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aGender.  aGendered conduct.  aLove.  aMedieval masculinity.  aMiddle Ages.  aRelationships.  aTroilus and Criseyde.1 aBowers, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalabrese, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrocker, Holly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoppelman, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Molly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re